metadata.name: Blendokush #237
metadata.description:
Inspired by the Android game, "Blendoku", this is an exploration into combining graduated colour arrays in different ways. Each piece begins with a set of 9 base colours. 
Keyboard 'c' will randomly change the way that the colours are combined while keeping all other variations the same.

metadata.name: Gestalt #152
metadata.description:
"Gestalt" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

A flurry of many elements derived from my past (and future) strewn across a single canvas. As random as things seem, collectively time tends to reveal hints of order in the chaos. Sometimes, more is more.

Controls:
‚Ä¢ Left-click/tap reassembles the piece with one less element each time
‚Ä¢ 'R' reassembles the piece with all elements
‚Ä¢ 'S' saves the output

metadata.name: Microgravity #164
metadata.description:
Microgravity is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Scale symmetry of abstract semiliquid forms.

Click on a section of the image to explore deeper.
- Use keys [0-9] to change the detail level.
- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "R" key to reset the coordinates.

metadata.name: a fleeting moment #31
metadata.description:
Abstract expressionism always has been, and always will be, my first love. With this piece, the initial premise was "can I write a bit of code that will render images in the style that I actually paint in real life?" 

It took several full days of poking and prodding, and I departed from the original mission once I had what I was looking for, but in general, I think I succeeded. My wife was looking over my shoulder at one point, and thought I was looking at a scan of one of my actual paintings, which sounds like success to me. 

Created with love in p5.js

metadata.name: Concrete #535
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksj√∏ (1910‚Äì1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksj√∏ designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksj√∏‚Äôs aim was to ‚Äúsoften‚Äù modernist architecture. He invented ¬´Natural Concrete¬ª, a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions‚Äîusing code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksj√∏: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‚ÄòS‚Äô to save an image at current resolution or ‚ÄòP‚Äô to save a high-resolution file at 6000√ó6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau ¬∑ Made with p5.js & glsl ¬∑ Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Antiflow #191
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." -¬†Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about¬†how opposing¬†forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea¬†reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental¬†law of nature baked into the¬†very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise¬†from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing¬†forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique¬†set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio¬†is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: Heat Death #54
metadata.description:
Heat Death is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

It aims to produce variation and detail from minimal logic.

The source code uses p5.js and consists of around 180 lines of code. It has been left unminified for the interested viewer to learn more.
